narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments:
- Finding different ways to solve a problem and understanding why each way works
- Understanding how all our previous knowledge builds up to enable us to solve calc 2 problems
Just a general introduction into more advanced topics of single variable calculus.
The foundations of calculus

I learned a number of higher-level skills in Calculus revolving around one variable including series, sequences, series tests, new methods of integration, improper integrals, polar equations, parametric equations, and more.
I learned how to solve parametric equations and what those even are
I was able to work on quantitative skills and generally improve my understanding of calculus
Analytical skills and a better understanding of how single variable calculus applies to the world
I learned more about Calculus II concepts, such as sequences and series, areas, parametric equations, and integrals.
I learned a lot about calculus.
I think I learned a lot about math and understanding many of the different skills in math. It taught me how to pace math and different tricks to do math and understand everything.
I developed my knowledge in calculus in this course.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I think the format of the course was really good with homework, PSets, and class time. If I could propose some improvements I would also explain why what we are learning is applicable to real world situations.
Very well organized, instructor did VERY well in introducing and exploring topics quickly.
Very fast-paced, but understandable as it is a condensed summer course. Pre-class "exploration" quizzes could be removed.
Really engaging structure, but there might have been just a little too much content for the timeframe.
Amazing professor!!! Very long hours though during the summer
would be better in person but otherwise was great in every aspect
The biggest strength of the class was our professor, Rachel. She is an excellent instructor and helped us understand the material. No weaknesses.
I thought this was a really strong course.

Strengths: Very well explained, obviously the use of technology made some things more different than an in person class would have been. There was a little bit of problems with engagement- and that was based on the fact that it was a Zoom class. 

I think that a lot of the problems in engagement would be improved through the advent of in-person classes.
Was a hard course to take online, could be improved by being on campus, couldn't be done this year on campus but would've been better in person

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes. I think it was a great accelerated version of Calc 2 and touched on all the essentials. I also found the zoom setup very efficient.
Absolutely- if they are looking for a challenging but manageable exploration of calculus.
Yes!

I would definitely recommend this course if a student needed to get the math requirement out of the way. Otherwise, I would still recommend a regular semester course because it was very dense, however it was manageable.
Yes! IF you have to take 115 take it in the summer definitely not the normal semester
yes definitely as a pre req for most majors

Yes absolutely, especially with Rachel! Rachel was an amazing professor!! She was so engaging and energetic during our long Zoom sessions and always made herself available to answer our questions. She is easily the best math professor I have ever had. She was incredibly kind and understanding and super passionate about calculus. The material was not always the easiest or most intuitive, but she explained everything really well. I would definitely take another class with her in the future!!
Yes, if you need/want to learn calc 2.

I would recommend taking this class in order to avoid taking it in the normal year. It was hard, but it was very well-organized and I understood everything going on regardless of the pace of the class because of how the class was planned.
yes, especially with professor diethorn because she is a great professor who is very committed to the success of her students.
I would because I felt I had a better grasp on calculus after this course.
